SIMPLE: plaint
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plaint
<hw>Plaint</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>plainte</ets>, <ets>pleynte</ets>, F. <ets>plainte</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>plangere</ets>, <ets>planctum</ets> (<ets>plancta</ets>, fem. p.
p.), to beat, beat the breast, lament. Cf. <er>Complain</er>,
<er>Plague</er>, <er>Plangent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Audible
expression of sorrow; lamentation; complaint; hence, a mournful song; a
lament.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au>⟦ldquo⟧The Psalmist's mournful
<xex>plaint</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Wordsworth.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An accusation or protest on account of an
injury.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There are three just grounds of war with Spain: one of
<qex>plaint</qex>, two upon defense.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A private memorial tendered to a
court, in which a person sets forth his cause of action; the exhibiting
of an action in writing.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1094 --></p>

<p><ent>Plaintful</ent>⟦br⟧
